betterquesting:10.desc:8:
Make the Improved Kiln (you will need a vanilla hopper to place on the top to complete the multiblock). You may noticed that this is just the Immersive Engineering blast furnace but for Telomerase it has been re-purposed for automating stone age and bronze age kiln related tasks. The kiln will output ash as a byproduct of combustion.

Once you get electricity (RF) make sure to make a couple of Kiln Preheaters to improve the speed of this bad boy!

No idea why you would ever need this (plus I find it kind of uh-gu-ly) but hey, it's available. It's a beefed up coke oven that is quite fast and also gives a little bonus to the outputs. It's also mega expensive.

These capacitors in boxes will help make sure your electrical tools stay charged when on the go!

The induction chargers will charge any items in your inventory that need it.

Some neat redstone enhancing mods have been included so go wild.

- Piston Everything allows you to push (most) tile entities with a regular piston
- Hopper Ducts will help you move and sort items with ease
- Pistronics allows you to build crazy contraptions
- Restone Paste will defy the rules of classical redstone

Make bandages to cure your wounds better! A primitive bandage works in a pinch, but it wont completely cure the wound. A cloth bandage will remove the debuffs and significantly decrease the healing time. A cast works similarly so for a Fracture, instantly healing it in fact! A sterile bandage, which is made by soaking a cloth bandage in a barrel or vessel of Distilled Alcohol. A sterile bandage will act just like a cloth bandage but will also heal the player 100 HP, and can be used even when you're not injured, as a source of health!

Fruit trees are propagated by adding at least 40oz of fruit to the middle of a large vessel, with the rest of the tiles containing at least two dirt. When the fruit rots enough to become a tree, 8 dirt will be consumed and you will get a sapling. Make a squeezer to get the juice out of fruit, or use stone hoppers with a smooth stone weight. Put the fruit you want to press in a stone hopper above a barrel. Then place the smooth stone block on top of that stack. The stone will plop into the hopper and start pressing juice. To make alcohol out of the fruit juice, leave a small piece of fruit in a cooking area (knife on ground) and wait for things to get yeasty. Then put the juice in a barrel, add the yeasty fruit, then seal it up.

Making a boat to go to other areas to get more iron ore may help. Get a barrel of pitch to make a boat. If you need a better boat, craft a boat with a copper plate to get your first level of ship, and upgrade it with subsequent materials. For more info, look up ships mod

Explanation: Iron, steel, and pig iron are all mostly the element iron, with varying levels of carbon and impurities such as silicates or other oxides. There are many ways to use each of these materials, and a few ways to go between them. Pig iron is high impurity steel that comes out of a TFC+ blast furnace. You can also make it with a bloom and coal coke in an arc furnace. High carbon steel can be made with pig iron in the arc furnace or on the anvil, or with steel and coal coke in the arc furnace. Steel can be made from high carbon steel on the anvil or in the arc furnace, or melting many types of steel components.

Get some garnierite. This can be done by mining in gabbro or with limonite powder. To extract "Small Garnierite" from limonite powder, leave limonite powder in a barrel of nitric acid. Nitric acid is made with lye and ammonium chloride. Ammonium chloride can be made from sal ammoniac which is found around lava. Lye can be made from soda ash or potash in limewater. 

Make weak steel by melting proper percentage of steel, nickel or nickel ore, and black bronze. High carbon black steel is made from welding pig iron to weak steel. Then refine into black steel on the anvil.

The weak version of colored steels are made in the arc furnace or in a crucible. Please be careful to use the correct proportions. High carbon Red or blue steel can be made from welding black steel and the weak version of the colored steel. Red or Blue steel is made from working their high carbon version on the anvil or processing it in the arc furnace.

The weak version of colored steels are made in the arc furnace or in a crucible. Please be careful to use the correct proportions. High carbon Red or blue steel can be made from welding black steel and the weak version of the colored steel. Red or Blue steel is made from working their high carbon version on the anvil or processing it in the arc furnace.
You are now able to move water source blocks and lava source blocks, just make red steel buckets to move water and blue steel buckets to move lava.
Pick up 10 stones and 10 sticks, right click 2 or more rocks in hand to open the knapping interface and haft the toolheads to make tools.

Cut 64 (some will be left over) thatch with knife from grass and pick up 2 sticks. Hold 5 straw in hand and right click the ground. Make clothing, a basket, and cordage, then combine with sticks to make a thatch roof to stay warm!

Take a knife and right click on a tree. You should eventually get resin. You will then need poles. Trees can drop poles when chopped, so will bushes, or alternatively craft a knife with a log to get a pole. Then take your resin and craft with a pole to get a walking stick - you will walk faster without using more hunger! 

Then, you can craft a knife with a pole to make a wooden spear. Take the spear and shift+right click it into the ground to place it. You can then make a teepee by placing 7 spears in a u-shape and taking 20 wicker (made by crafting a pole with an axe) and right clicking on ground in the middle of the spears. A warmer teepee can be made with 4 spears in a square, one apart from each other (on the corners) and 4 medium hides or 2 large hides (use Bear/wolf furs in cold climates!) instead of wicker. A teepee will let you sleep but wont set your spawn. 

You can also make torches out of resin, straw, and a stick, or out of a stick and pitch, which is made by melting resin. You will need to invent fire before you can light your torch but beware, lit torches can light nearby things on fire!

Clay is an essential resource in TFC+. Find 45 clay and right click with 5 in hand to shape it. You can find clay by looking for goldenrod (yellow flowers) on the ground or by looking around rivers and lakes. Dirt also has a chance to drop clay but it's quite rare.

Ceramic jugs will allow you to carry water and drink faster. Ceramic molds will allow you to shape early-game metals. Vessels are used to store and process items/fluids. Bowls will help you find your first metal!

Find 5 sticks 8 logs and 8 straw. With 2 sticks make a firestarter. In a safe area throw 3 sticks on ground and use firestarter on it. Food can be cooked here with fuel and relighting with firestarter. To fire pottery dig a one block hole, fill with pottery by right click, then use staw and logs and finally the firestarter. Do not put out fire. If you want to fire larger quantities of ceramics, make a large kiln, with 48 solid, non gravity blocks in a configuration specified by the wiki: https://plus.terrafirmacraft.com/Kiln

Find 32 straw and 32 dirt and 32 stick, fill ceramic bucket with water. Throw 32 straw and 32 dirt on ground, then use water bucket to make mud. Make wattle by crafting 4 sticks. To make wattle and daub, use mud on wattle. To make wet mud brick, craft one mud. Then set out to ry by shift+right clicking on the ground. After 8 hours in the sun (not raining or night) they will dry. 4 dry mud bricks can be made into mud brick block. Mud brick products melt in rain, so use thatch or other roof.

Sometimes in TFC+ you will get injured, when you take a large amount of damage. These deal ongoing damage and hamper the player, so it's important to treat them quickly! Depending on the type of wound, you will want different treatment. For a fracture, using a splint (later a cast) and for a cut or wound use a bandage.

Find 10 pieces of small (10 unit) copper ore either by making a panning tool with a ceramic bowl, or by picking ore off the ground. Copper ores include: chalcocite, chalcopyrite, malachite ,native copper, and tetrahedrite. Then, put the ore into a ceramic vessel and fire it in a pit kiln. When it is ready, put the tool molds in the ceramic vessel and wait for them to fill up. A pickaxe, saw and pospecter's pick each cost 100 units of metal so choose wisely which tool you will make first. A pickaxe will allow you to mine more copper, a prospecter's pick will help you find more copper and a saw will help you craft more items. Once the molds have cooled craft the tool heads with a stick to obtain the tool.
To make a crafting table, use a saw to make planks out of wood, then make wood blocks, and four blocks make a crafting table. It will expand your current 4x4 one until death.

There are many food plants in the tfc world, some are grains, some are vegetables. Picking them up is a good idea, as they will die in winter, unless they are grapes. To plant your seeds, till dirt in an area that gets plenty of water (evidenced by your hoe) and plant them. Depending on what latitude you are on, they will die earlier or later in the year, so plant at the right time for your area (start out with mid spring?)When the plants are harvested, they will give you a seed and an amount of crop. Use the S button to consolidate food of the same type. Foods can be cooked to increase the hunger they fill. Grains can be ground in a quern to make fours, which can be combined with water to make dough, which when baked in an oven makes bread. Look up the way to make an oven.

Kill an animal. Remember they will fight back! It should drop a lot of meat. Meat can be salted, dried, smoked, or cooked. Salt is obtained from grinding down rock salt in a quern,  or boiling saltwater. Smoking meat can be done by erecting two walls with solid blocks, then using string to make a line across them. Use a string per 160oz slice to hang them on the string, then make a fire pit underneath and keep it going to smoke the meat.
Sandwich makin’ is done on a cooking surface. Use a knife on a solid block to make one. Put bread and your ingredients in the table to make a sandwich.

Sisal fibers are a byproduct of agave processing, and jute is created by soaking jute plants.

Strings can be obtained using a spindle. A spindle can process flax fibers, cotton and wool
Silk String can be obtained by killing spiders

Make a rope and some fences to get a pen ready and some animals in your pen. What, you expected to walk up to a bison and milk it? Animals you take from the wild will be unaccustomed to you. Slowly feed them small amounts of food per day to increase their liking of you. 

Domesticated bovines can be milked and this milk can be turned into cheese!

More information can be found on the TFC+ wiki here: https://plus.terrafirmacraft.com/Animal_Husbandry

Wolves and bears can be found in the wild. Bears will easily kill you if you are carrying exposed meat in your inventory, same with wolves. If you kill them, you will get their pelts. These can be crafted into clothing to wear. Only wear it when i's below freezing though! Something easy to make is a hood. Craft a pelt with a knife to get a hood.

Once you reach 14 wrought iron ingots, weld them together to make double ingots, then turn them into an anvil. 

But wait, you're not done collecting iron. In order to make steel, you will need 8 iron double sheets and 12 iron sheets.
Gather clay, kaolinite, graphite for fire clay. Make five fire clay for every crucible you want. You will need two to make steel, and it is convenient to have a third to melt down nonferrous ores.

TFC+ offers a comprehensive and powerful mechanical power system. Find a high up spring or dig down near water and set up a waterwheel under falling water. The farther the waterfall the more power. Transfer the power through axles and gears to power a millstone or bellows. See https://plus.terrafirmacraft.com/Mechanisms

You can change the speed of your axles using gears. Big gears connected to small gears will speed up and vice versa. Keep in mind, high spin rates can induce a lot of load and will require you to build more waterwheels! you can reduce load during transmission by decreasing the spin rate before and increasing it back up at the location you use the power.

In Telomerase, the Immersive Engineering windmills also work with mechanisms. You will need to place an Engineer's Bearing behind the windmill in order to get mechanical power from it. Windmills aren't as powerful as waterwheels but they do look amazing!
Gather fire clay bricks and blast furnace, wrought iron sheets, make a tuyere, and make a blast furnace multiblock as in https://plus.terrafirmacraft.com/Blast_Furnace
The carpenter is very useful. Despite its unassuming name, many mid game and end game processes will use it. Make a carpenter.

Make some tools to start engineering. You don't need a degree to do this engineering. Make an engineer's hammer with a bronze hammer head, two string, and a stick. Make an Engineer’s Manual with a book and a lever. This will show you how to do all multiblocks and other useful info.

Cheapest textbook i've ever bought

Two major things you will need are coal coke and creosote oil. To start, make 27 coke bricks. Make a cube with them. Click one side with the engineer's hammer. Put one coal in it to start making coal coke and pitch. Pitch can be put in a forestry still or tfc+ still (two large vessels, one sealed one on a fire pit, another next to it, with a blowpipe on the hot one) to make creosote oil. Treated wood can be made by placing wood plank blocks in barrels of creosote oil. It will be used to make many things.

Make nitroglycerine with the reaction chamber! Make plant oil from oily mash and use the reaction chamber to make glycerine, and nitric acid from ammonium chloride in same way. Use the IE refinery to make you very own explosive.

Make some lye with a carpenter, using limewater and potash or soda ash. Nuclear power? Yes please! Find some pitchblende and grind it up, then craft 8 with one lye to make yellowcake. Make a Thermionic fabricator (catalytic converter) and connect it to power. Add a platinum bar as a catalyst, then use yellowcake and ammonium chloride powder to get uranyl nitrate. Use a barrel or squeezer to get ammonium chloride. Make ammonium diuranate with the ammonium chloride and uranyl nitrate via a carpenter or barrel. Make a reaction chamber. Find some fluorite gemstones. Grind the flourite into powder in a quern or crusher. Make Hydrofluoric acid with fluorite, charcoal, and fresh water in the reaction chamber. It's a bad idea to put Hydrofluoric acid in a glass bottle so make a lead bottle instead. Craft or use a carpenter to use the hydrofluoric acid and ammonium diuranate to make uranium hexafluoride. Separate it in the centrifuge to get enriched uranium powder!

Phew. Let's hope all that was worth it

Redstone is obtained by Cinnabar and has vanilla functionality. Many redstone components are availabe for crafting!

Redstone will prove vital for automation as well as a few crafting recipes. Make sure to get some!

To make electrical connections, place wire connectors on a block that can input or output power. Next, connect a wire coil to the connectors. The different types of wire connectors transmit different levels of RF per tick

LV: 256
MV: 1024
HV: 4096

Wires can transmit much more than the connectors but may incur losses over long distances. To minimize losses, higher tier wires should be used (however for low power applications, MV is better for long distance transmission)

Wire cutters are very useful tools for working with wires. you can cut a wire without breaking a connector

Relays are useful for connecting mutliple coils togeter in order to join or split wires without a connector (which would bottleneck the transfer rate!) This way you can trasmit power long distances without many wires!

To harvest RF (redstone flux(power)) from your environment, consider making a kinetic dynamo. They passively harvest motion by virtue of a waterwheel or windmill or mechanics which you may have made earlier. Windmills have to have access to wind, and you will get a marginal increase in power output the higher the windmill. IE Water Wheels must have access to flowing water all flowing in the same rotational direction. up to three waterwheels can be stacked onto one dynamo for a 3 block wide waterwheel. 

Make a kinetic dynamo and power it with rotational power. Then you can tap power from any side of the dynamo.

One may wish to make a thermoelectric generator. Lava and water are good choices, but not necessarily the most efficient. One could also use enriched uranium blocks for heat. To set up, place your heat source on one or two orthogonal sides of the generator (doing this in the ground is clean) and on the opposite side place the cold source. One can then place a wire connector on the 3rd orthogonal side to get power. More information here: https://ftb.gamepedia.com/Thermoelectric_Generator

The arc furnace is a pain to make, but is extremely useful. A tentative list of what you will need is listed: 
6  wrought iron sheets
14 concrete slabs
4  concrete blocks
35 fire brick bricks
28 mortar
14 iron mechanical components
8  steel mechanical components
74 steel rods

Use the engineers manual to make the blocks you need. They are listed with the question mark under heavy machinery ---> arc furnace. Hit with a hammer in the right place to turn it into an arc furnace.

Next, make 3 graphite electrodes for the arc furnace. Once the electrodes are in place, you will need a lot of electricity to run this thing!

There are three structures needed to make the biodiesel, refinery, squeezer and still. You should already have the squeezer and still. Turn oily mash into plant oil in the squeezer, and use the still to distill alcoholic beverages into ethanol. Make the refinery, and put plant oil and ethanol in the slots via buckets to start making biodiesel. Neat tech, isn't it? You will want to burn your biodiesel to generate RF. Do this by making a biodiesel generator. This can power the excavator

Biodiesel is also used by the Mining Drill, which is a useful tool that can break a 2x2 or 3x3 area at once. Beware of caevins though! The steel drill head (in normal Immersive Engineering this is the iron head) is the first tier and the diamond drill head is the higher tier.
Make the metal press. It will forge you metal bars, sheets, and gears using power.
Make the crusher. It is very fast for crushing items into powders and also gives you slightly more yeild!

To use the excavator correctly, make core samplers, charge your capacitors, and probe the areas around you for minerals. In the same chunk that the core sampler detects minerals, set up an excavator.  If you power it, it will mine ores for you
Make a Revolver. That's all

Find and get one raw igneous stone (Diorite, Gabbro, Granite, Andesite, Basalt, Dacite, Rhyolite) To obtain a raw stone item you will need to mine all adjacent blocks to the stone block. Then place it where you want to have your anvil. Use a hammer on it to turn it into an anvil. This anvil will only be able to weld copper. 

To get a better anvil you will need a lot more copper. Collecting nuggets is not really going to cut it... lets get mining! Craft two logs on top of each other and a saw to the left or right of the top one in order to obtain support beams. Use an upside down "U" made of 7 beams to prevent cave ins while mining. Use a pick to mine a bunch of copper, you will need a lot. You can find copper veins by looking near copper nuggets or by using a prospectors pick.

Collect as many of the following (dolomite, marble, limestone, chalk(rocks),  shells) as you can. Cook them in a ceramic vessel in a kiln to create lime. 

Lime can be crafted into flux but lime is also useful on it's own. Flux can also be obtained from salammoniac which generates near lava as well as from grinding borax which is an ore.

Gather many logs to turn into charcoal. Dig a pit and place logs in the pit. Toss a lit torch on the logs and cover them in non-flammable solid blocks as soon as it ignites. For more information, check the wiki: https://plus.terrafirmacraft.com/Charcoal

Once you have eight charcoal, place them and surround it with stone/cobble/bricks on the bottom and all four sides. To use your forge during rain, place a chimney block 2 blocks above the charcoal.(one air block in between) then light the charcoal with a fire starter to make a forge. You will find that the Bow Drill is very useful for lighting the forge! You will need to refuel the forge, but the block itself will not go away. If you have already found coal, you can also use a coal block instead of 8 charcoal and coal is even better fuel for the forge.

When you smelt copper, you can pour it into a ceramic ingot mold so that when it cools you will get an ingot. Heat two ingots in your forge and use your stone anvil and flux to weld your ingots together to create double ingots. You will need a total of 7 double ingots in order to create a copper anvil.

Find the requisite materials for bronze. In TFC+ there are 3 types of bronze: Bronze (aka Tin Bronze), Black Bronze, and Bismuth Bronze. Alloying can be done in either a ceramic vessel or in a crucible. For help with alloy amounts check the wiki: https://plus.terrafirmacraft.com/Alloys

Make an anvil in the same way you made a copper anvil. One anvil must be made of the same type of bronze (You only need one anvil total of any of the three types).
Once you want to move onto the iron age, collect 32 bronze ingots. Make them into double bronze sheets and then craft a bloomery by putting the 8 double sheets in an "O" shape.

betterquesting:10.name:8: Destroyer of Stars, Creator of Bars
betterquesting:10.desc:8: Work the bloom on an anvil to get wrought iron.

Collect enough hide to make the amount of leather you want. (small = 1, medium = 2, large = 4). Put lime in a barrel or vessel of fresh water to get limewater. Place raw hides into the barrel, until they become soaked hides (seal the barrel). Once they are soaked hides, place them on a large or stacked log, then scrape it with a knife. Place the scraped hide in a barrel of water and seal it to make a prepared hide. Once you have a prepared hide, make another barrel and fill it with fresh  water. Put one of the following types of logs in (Acacia, Birch, Chestnut, Douglas Fir, Fever, Hickory, Limba, Mahogany, Maple, Oak, or Sequoia) and seal it until it becomes tannin. Once you have a barrel of tannin, soak the prepared hides till you get leather. 3 leather and 6 planks will give you a bellows, which when placed facing the block above a forge and activated, will increase the fuel consumption in return for heating the forge to a higher temperature.

The first multiblock you will want to work on for nuclear power is the Reactor. A Reactor is a made up of the following: Control Rod (for every column of Fuel Rods), Fuel Rod(s), a Reactor Controller, a Reactor Access Port, at least 2 Reactor Coolant Ports, enough Reactor Casing or Reactor Glass (only on the faces) to encase your entire reactor. Salt Water or Fresh Water source blocks can be added inside the air pockets in the reactor to make it even more fuel efficient. In the end, the shape will be a rectangular prism or cube, so any shape other than the minimum (3x3x3) will have space for water.

Once done, the multiblock will take on an alternate texture to signify its completeness. The access port will take fuel in and move the waste (depleted uranium) out. The Reactor accepts Distilled Water through any blue colored Coolant Port (right click with Engineer's Hammer to change) and steam will be output out of any red colored Fluid Port (Use an Immersive Engineering Pump for high pump rate). The control rod is used to manually slow down the reactor. The controller allows you to control the reactor.

Nuclear waste can be converted into vanilla glowstone.

If you are having trouble, please use the provided schematic named BigReactors-Starter (default hotkey "/") to get you started!




yay

The other multiblock for nuclear power is the Steam Turbine. How big you build this is is up to you, but near to minimum size (5x5x5) will still generate a large amount of energy. (expect a little less than 1.5k RF/t for the most simple reactor-turbine setup)

The Turbine multiblock is a box whose edges must be made out of Turbine Casing, the faces can be Turbine Casing or Turbine Glass. You will need a Turbine Controller, a Rotor Bearing a Power Port and a Fluid Port. You will need several Rotor Shafts and Rotor Blades (the more you have, the higher steam input you can process). Lastly, you will need Coil Blocks to surround the Rotor Shafts at the opposite end to the bearing.

The completed multiblock accepts steam through any red colored Fluid Port (right click with Engineer's Hammer to change) and distilled water can be pumped out of any blue colored Fluid Port (Use an Immersive Engineering Pump for high pump rate).

If you are having trouble, please use the provided schematic named BigReactors-Starter (default hotkey "/") to get you started!

You've made it. All the way. And now it's time to reap the rewards! Aluminum is a late game metal that has high level uses. The ore is bauxite. Turn bauxite into alumina by reacting it in the arc furnace with lye. Then use fluorite powder and cryolite to react with alumina to get in the arc furnace. Once you have aluminum, make the endgame gear: The Railgun, the Compound Bow, the Hang Glider and most importantly: The Chainsaw. Congratulations!
Get Daki
Play the TFC theme on it and you might attract a bone girl.
Make an unkown ingot. Waste your metal, I know what you did...
"Bruh why do we have so many plum trees?"
Kinda sus
Don't look it up...
Make a full suit of red steel armor and wonder where all your materials went...
Make a full set of blue steel armor so you wont die when all your naked friends will.
Mooooooom, can we have the skull in the quest book?!

A loom is a useful tool for weaving various cloths. Sisal and Jute fibers can be woven into burlap and other strings can be woven into various cloths. These cloths have many uses including clothing and bedding.

A faster loom can be created using wooden lumber. But you will need a saw first!

Bricks are excellent building materials but you need to create a chisel first to make the bricks. Next make mortar with limewater and craft the two together!

Bricks are also useful for making chimneys to put over your forge to keep it dry in the rain.

What would TFC+ be without alcohol. Fruits can be squeezed into fruit juice which can then be fermented into alcohol. Grains and sugars can be added to water and fermented into alcohol as well. You will need to place a yeasty food item into a barrel in order to ferment the liquid.

Once alcohol is made, it can then be distilled using two ceramic vessels, one which is over a firepit. Put the alcohol into the one over the firepit, put a ceramic blowpipe in the item slot and seal the vessel. You will then start to collect distilled alcohol!

These accessories are very useful for working with electricity

Wire cutters are very useful tools for working with wires. you can cut a wire without breaking a connector

Relays are useful for connecting mutliple coils togeter in order to join or split wires without a connector (which would bottleneck the transfer rate!) This way you can trasmit power long distances without many wires!

The engineer's voltmeter is useful for observing energy storage in capactiors and devices
The squeezer is under the biodiesel section in the IE manual. Compared to the forestry squeezer, the IE one is much faster since it can squeeze up to 9 items at a time!
Make a capacitor that is according to your materials and needs. The different voltages (HV,MV,LV) signify how much RF can be stored.

Windmills and waterwheels are pretty straightforward using a kinetic dynamo.

Additionally, in Telomerase, you can place a Wooden Axle Bearing item next to a kinetic dynamo and place an axle in it. rotating this axle will generate power! The faster it rotates, the more energy is produced but at an increasing load to the mechanisms. Therefore it is beneficial to make multiple kinetic dynamos to get the most out of it.

The peat fired engine and the clockwork engine are two single-block generators added by forestry. They aren't all that powerful but they can be useful if you just need a small amount of power and don't want to deal with wiring up the place.

The Squeezer and the Still are very useful since they automate some of the labor intensive tasks in TFC+. For example, the Squeezer can squeeze fruit into juice and the Still can distill alcohol.

Move fluids manually with buckets, bottles or a pipette or automatically with the Immersive Engineering pump.

Make the refinery, and put plant oil or olive oil and ethanol in the slots via buckets or pipes from the exterior to start making biodiesel. Neat tech, isn't it? 

Note: the refinery is much more efficient in converting the reactants into biodiesel compared to a barrel.
You will want to burn your biodiesel to generate RF. Do this by making a biodiesel generator. This outputs a LOT of power!

Biodiesel is also used by the Mining Drill, which is a useful tool that can break a 2x2 or 3x3 area at once. Beware of caevins though! The steel drill head (in normal Immersive Engineering this is the iron head) is the first tier and the diamond drill head is the higher tier.

Beekeeping in Telomerase is quite extensive! First find a beehive. Beehives are more common in areas with high rainfall so look for lush forests. In order to open a beehive, you right click... BUT WAIT you need to light a campfire underneath in order to pacify the bees. Open it up and take the fertile honeycomb.

Create a basket hive and place flowers around it and place your fertile honeycomb into the basket hive. The hive will produce combs now!

Forestry adds it's own version of beekeeping which can be acessed by crafting a fertile honeycomb. The crafting recipe will give you a queen and drones. Create a bee house and start breeding your bees!

Forestry beekeeping can be automated to produce useful products.
Backpacks are very useful for expanding your inventory. Each variant can only hold certain items but these items are the kinds of items you will find on your journey!
Progress from nothing through the Mesolithic, Neolithic, and eventually even Chalcolithic with the advent of copper!
Work Iron and make your first real machines so you dont have to power everything by hand. Then advance into steel and steel alloys to rule the world!
Now you've made it to Industrialization. Use IE and Forestry to automate previously tedious processes and create more powerful tools to expand your base.
Discover the power of alloying and create bronze and better metalworking technology.
These late-game quests are designed to satisfy your completionist grindset
A few in-jokes from the developers and meme quests.
